\section{Introduction}

The package \texttt{BioCro} started as a way to continue work on the
ideas developed in the WIMOVAC model. WIMOVAC was developed by Stephen
Long and Steve Humphries
(http://www.life.illinois.edu/plantbio/wimovac/) and there have been
several publications using this model. I have used the model for some
initial efforts at modeling \emph{Miscanthus} $\times$ \emph{giganteus}.

\subsection{Leaf-level Photosynthesis}

Since WIMOVAC originate as a photosynthesis model we can start with a
simple example. For the C$_4$ photosynthesis model the best reference
is Collatz et al. (1992). 

<<ex-photo>>=
c4photo(1500,25,0.7)
@ 

This example shows that with irradiance of 1500, temperature of 25 and
relative humidity of 0.7 (70\%) the predicted CO$_2$ assimilation is
30.5, the stomatal conductance 278 and the intercellular CO$_2$ is
205. For units and other details see \texttt{?c4photo}.

There is an equivalent function \texttt{c3photo} which is closely
based on the c3 photosynthesis model described in WIMOVAC. Notice that
the parameters and interpretation are different from the
\texttt{c4photo} function.

The previous functions are relevant for leaf-level
photosynthesis. Scaling up to the canopy level is not trivial since it
requires developing a light macro environment which simulates the
partitioning between direct and diffuse radiation (see function
\texttt{lightME}). The function \texttt{sunML} is used to predict the
proportion of light for each layer of a multiple layered canopy. 

\subsection{Canopy Photosynthesis}

Finally the function \texttt{CanA} integrates the previous functions
to simulate canopy CO$_2$ assimilation for a complete canopy. This
function also simulates transpiration based on Penman-Monteith, Penman
and Priestly. The default at the moment is Priestly because
Penman-Monteith is producing values for canopy conductance that are
too low. 

The \texttt{CanA} function is designed to run at an hourly
timestep. The inputs should all be of length 1. See \texttt{?CanA} for details.


<<ex2>>=
nlay <- 8
res <- CanA(lai=3, doy=200, hr=20, solar=1500, temp=25, rh=0.7, 
            windspeed=2, nlayers=nlay)
res
@ 

The distribution of leaves in the sun and in the shade
(Fig. ~\ref{fig:plotCanALeaves}). This is the proportion of the LAI
which is in the shade and in the sun in each layer.

<<>>=
apply(res$LayMat[,3:4], 2, sum)
@ 

In this example, 1.35 m$^2$ of leaf are in the sun and 1.65 of $m^2$
are in the shade for a total of 3 LAI.

The amount of photosynthesis due to each layer is proportional to the
amount of sun and shaded leaves in each layer.

<<>>=
data(weather05)
doy200 <- weather05[weather05$doy == 200,]

lai <- 3
nlay <- 3
tmp2 <- NULL

for(i in 1:24){
  doy <- doy200[i,2]
  hr  <- doy200[i,3]
  solar <- doy200[i,4]
  temp <- doy200[i,5]
  rh <- 0.5
  ws <- 4

  tmp <- CanA(lai,doy,hr,solar,temp,rh,ws,nlayers=nlay,chi.l=1)$LayMat

  tmp <- cbind(hour=hr, layers=1:nlay,tmp)
  tmp2 <- rbind(tmp2,tmp)
     
}
@ 

